      {
        "paragraph_index": 4,
        "text": "### Chemistry Insight\n\nThe strong preference for the **linear di-ammine complex** [Ag(NH₃)₂]⁺ (log β₂ ≈ 7.5–8) is characteristic of d¹⁰ Ag⁺, which favors 2-coordinate linear geometry. This is the basis of **Tollens' reagent** ([Ag(NH₃)₂]⁺ in base), widely used to detect aldehydes. The negative ΔS values indicate an entropy penalty from ordering ammonia ligands around the metal, but the enthalpic gain (ΔH ≈ −58 kJ/mol for β₂) drives complex formation.\n\n---\n*Source: NIST SRD-46 (Critically Selected Stability Constants of Metal Complexes), metal_2 (Ag⁺) × ligand_10103 (Ammonia), 47 entries.*",
